Singular
notions:
1、 The inverse exists if and only if elimination produces n pivots
2、 The matrix A cannot have two different inverses

proof:
assume B and C are the inverse matrices of A.
BAC = BAC (BA)C = B(AC) C = B

3、

4、 Suppose there is a nonzero vector x such that Ax = O. Then A cannot have an inverse.
5、 The Inverse of a Product AB——reverse order
6、 For square matrices, an inverse on one side is automatically an inverse on the other side.
Gauss-Jordan Elimination
K->U->Diagonal->I
K is symmetric across its main diagonal. So is K^(-1)

2.6 Elimination = Factorization: A=LU

keywords:
A = LU
band matrix
notion:
factor A

More, L is just right

Each multiplier eij goes directly into its i, j position-unchanged-in the product of inverses which is L.

LDU

Lower triangular L times diagonal D times upper triangular U.

To solve Ax = b, first solve Lc = b, then solve Ux = c to get x.

nothing new just like we do in high school.

Elimination on A requires 1/3 n^3 multiplication and 1/3 n^3 substraction.

The right side costs a lot less than the left side! about n^2.


w represent nonzero diagonals below and also above its main diagonal.

matlab:

1.function [L U]=slu(A)
2.  [n n]= size(A);
3.  tol = 1e-6;
4.  for pivot = 1:n
5.    if abs(A(pivot,pivot)) < tol
6.      disp([num2str(pivot),"th pivot is zero"]) 
7.      return
8.      end
9.    L(pivot,pivot) = 1;
10.        for row = pivot+1:n
11.            L(row,pivot) = A(row,pivot)/A(pivot,pivot);
12.            for col = 1:n
13.                A(row,col) -= A(pivot,col)*L(row,pivot);
14.            end
15.        end
16.    U(pivot,:) = A(pivot,:);
17.    end
1.function x=slv(A,b)
2.  [L U] = slu(A);
3.  [n n] = size(A);
4.  s = 0;
5.  for row=1:n
6.    for col=1:row-1
7.      s += L(row,col)*c(col);
8.    end
9.    c(row) = b(row) - s;
10.  end
11.  s= 0;
12.  for row = n:-1:1
13.    for col = row+1:n
14.      s += U(row,col)*x(col);
15.     end
16.    x(row) = (c(row) - s)/U(row,row);
17.  end
18.  x = x';

notions:
1、
The simplest choices for the free variables are ones and zeros.

e.g.
x1 x2 x3 x4 x1 and x3 are pivot varibles. x2 and x4 are free varibles.
set x2 = 1 and x4 = 0 to solve a special solution s1
set x2 = 0 and x4 =1 to solve another special solution s2
then All solutions are linear combinations of s1 and s2.

2、
column space VS nullspace

The nullspace is a subspace. Its “dimension” is the number of free variables.

notion:
1、
a sequence of vectors is linearly independent if the only combination that gives the zero vector is 0v1+…+0vn.
2、
A set of vectors span a space if their linear combinations fill the space.

3/

4/
A basis for a vector space is a sequence of vectors with two properties:
The basis vectors are independent and span the space.

5/
There is one and only one way to write v as a combination of basis vectors.
suppose

done

6/
The pivot columns of A are a basis for its column space.

7/
The column spaces of A and R are different. Their bases are different.
The row space of A is same as the row space of R.

8/
there are many choices for basis vectors of a space. But the number of basis vectors doesn’t change.

9/
proof of 8
if two bases, v1,..,vm and w1,…,wn, n > m.
because v is basis, so

A is a m by n matrix. n > m , So Ax = 0 has nonzero solutoin. Because there’s utmost m pivots, so n columns are dependent. So exists a nonzero combination to make A’s columns to be zero vector.
So Wx = 0 exists nonzero solutions. So W can’t be basis, because columns in W are dependent.

10/
